This system will be built by visualizations which match to specific neurological batteries. In the abstract, a battery defines a set of measurement fields and how they relate. Then it can generate visualization modules both the raw and normalized fields as needed. A collection of these Battery objects will be combined into a Domain.

Those tests will likely become more complicated and less "abstract" as we go. But they're enough to represent each test and contain the information we need.

Now that we have a way of representing tests, lets merge them into domains and start visualizing.

In the abstract a domain collection should:

  • Hold the test calculator and hold a list a "defining_tests".
  • Manage the processing of the data with the calculator.
  • Hold Bokeh data like the ColumnDataSource, shared ranges, etc.
  • Combine the "defining_test" using an aggregation method.

Memory Domain

This domain is measured by the Brief Visiospatial Memory Test. It incorperates demographically adjusted norms from the Norman and Heaton datasets.

From Kate:

  • BVMT-R (done and "heaton" normalized)
    • Immediate Recall (BVMTimmed)
    • Delayed Recall (BVMTdelay)
    • Recognition (BVMTrecog)
  • SENAS WLL-I (In, but I only have "total", are there other important ones)
    • Total Score (WordListLearning_SENAS)
    • We no longer administer this, but all the 2013-2015 patients got it
  • HVLT-R (done and "heaton" normalized)
    • Total Learning
    • Delayed Recall
    • Recognition

Memory Domain - Pairplot

It is also important to be able to summarize the domain into a single number for deficit score calculations. This is automatically done using a mean across z-scaled features to account for the different levels of variability in each measure.

We can look at how the raw measurse compute up to the aggregated score.

Memory Domain - Deficit Scores

As well as seeing a set of deficit scores for each domain. A deficit score of 0 implies normal. Increasing numbers reflect z-scaled increases over the "normal" individual average across all tests in the domain.

Anything greater than 1 is considered "impaired"

{% raw %} 
mem_domain.build_deficit_plot()

Motor and Processing Speed

From Kate:

  • Grooved Pegboard (done and "heaton" normalized)
    • Dominant Hand (GroovedPegDom) and Nondominant Hand (GroovedPegNonDom)
    • Norms: Heaton, CNNS
  • Trail Making Test A (TrailA) (done and "heaton" normalized)
    • Norms: Heaton, CNNS
  • WAIS Coding (done, self-normalized)
    • (we previously used the WAIS-III version then switched to WAIS-IV)
    • WAIS-III Digit-Symbol Coding (WAIS3DigSymCoding)
    • WAIS-IV Coding (WAIS4DigSymCoding)
    • Norms for WAIS-III: WAIS-III Scoring assistant (another proprietary software I have the DVD for)
    • Norms for WAIS-IV: Advanced Clinical Solutions (another proprietary software we need to order or possibly borrow from Nancy Minniti)
    • Stroop (done and Norman norm
      • Stroop Word (Stroop.word)
      • Stroop Color (Stroop.color)
      • Norms: Norman

Executive Function

Beyond the memory domain there is also the Executive Function domain. This seems to be mainly using the Trails Making Test and the Stroop Word Test.

Currently only the Stroop test is implemented using the Norman regression based norms.

So, we need a quick way to normalize the un-normed fields. For simplicity we'll use a QuantileTransform and do it during the _load_data hook.

From Kate:

Executive function

  • Trail Making Test B (done and Heaton normed)
    • (TrailB)
    • Norms: Heaton, CNNS
  • Stroop (done and Norman normed)
    • Stroop Color Word (Stroop.colorword)
    • Stroop Interference (Stroop.interference)
    • Note: Stroop.interference is calculated as follows: [Stroop.colorword - (Stroop.word x Stroop.color)/(Stroop.word + Stroop.color)]
    • Norms: Manual (not preferred), Norman, MOANS/MOAANS
  • Wisconson Card Sort Test (done, self-normalized)
    • Categories Correct (mWCST.cat)
    • Perseverative Errors (mWCST.persev)
    • Total Errors (mWCST.errors)
    • Percent Perseverative Errors (a calculated variable, not yet created; formula is mWCST.persev/mWCST.errors)
    • Norms: Manual (not preferred), CNNS

Attention and Working Memory

These are primarily starting in a placeholder stage as I get all of the normalization schemes together.

From Kate:

Attention and working memory

  • SENAS Working Memory (various variables) (no longer administered)
    • Norms: SENAS (no longer needed)

WAIS-IV Digit Span

  • Primary scores that will contribute to GDS: (done and Self normed)

    • forward (DigitsForwardWAIS4)
    • backward (DigitsBackwardWAIS4)
    • sequencing (DigitsSequencingWAIS4)

  • Additional scores:

    • total score (DigitSpan)
    • longest span forward (LDSFWAIS4)
    • longest span backward (LDSBWAIS4)
    • longest span sequencing (LDSSWAIS4)
    • Norms: manual (not preferred), preferred is Advanced Clinical Solutions (another proprietary software; Im looking into obtaining it)

Visuospatial Doamin

Also, mostly just placeholders.

Visuospatial

  • Clock Drawing

    • Command (ClockCommand, ClockCommand2)
    • Copy (ClockCopy, ClockCopy2)
    • Primary scores that will contribute to GDS:
      • Schretlen scoring (ClockCommand2 and ClockCopy2, which become Clock1 and Clock2 in CNNS)
      • CNNS norms
    • Additional scores
      • Rouleau scoring (ClockCommand and ClockCopy): cutoffs from protocol sheet (not preferred)

  • ROCF

    • Score (ROCF)
    • Time (ROCFtime)
    • (note: time will not contribute to the GDS)
    • Norms: manual (not preferred), CNNS (to be included)
  • BVMT-R Copy (BVMTcopy)
    • Norms: test has a low ceiling and non-normal distribution; no good norms available, and certainly no demographically adjusted norms; options include inverse normal transformation and a binary cutoff at 10 or 11; we may or may not include this in the GDS
{% raw %}
